<dl id="n54121t"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54121t">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54121t"> 121(t)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Minister of Crime, <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54121t"><li>FW 242.11 </li><li><a href="../../flex/kd/lexkd.htm#n54121t">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kd/l39kd.htm#n54121t">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54121t">MS BL 47477-286</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:423 <a name="kad9" href="../../FF/fdra/kda.htm#kdd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kd/kdd10.htm#n54121t">Draft: II.1&sect;4.10</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><i>Master Kung considered taking service with a rebellious officer but did not do so. Appointed to the governorship of a town he accomplished some very notable reforms leading to his appointment to the ministry of Public Works and later to the more responsible position as <mark>Minister of Crime</mark>.</i> <small> Carl Crow, <a name="CCMK" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CCMK"><cite title="source">Master Kung. The Story of Confucius</cite></a> (Sep 1937) 152</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
